#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1124(title) 
msgid "Overview"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1126(para) 
msgid "This release of <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> adds features that have been requested for years, such as easy-to-use replication, a mass permission-changing facility, and anonymous code blocks. While past major releases have been conservative in their scope, this release shows a bold new desire to provide facilities that new and existing users of <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> will embrace. This has all been done with few incompatibilities. Major enhancements include:"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1143(para) 
msgid "Built-in replication based on log shipping. This advance consists of two features: Streaming Replication, allowing continuous archive (<acronym>WAL</acronym>) files to be streamed over a network connection to a standby server, and Hot Standby, allowing continuous archive standby servers to execute read-only queries. The net effect is to support a single master with multiple read-only slave servers."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1154(para) 
msgid "Easier database object permissions management. <link linkend=\"sql-grant\"><command>GRANT</command>/<command>REVOKE IN SCHEMA</command></link> supports mass permissions changes on existing objects, while <link linkend=\"sql-alterdefaultprivileges\"><command>ALTER DEFAULT PRIVILEGES</command></link> allows control of privileges for objects created in the future. Large objects (BLOBs) now support permissions management as well."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1166(para) 
msgid "Broadly enhanced stored procedure support. The <link linkend=\"sql-do\"><command>DO</command></link> statement supports ad-hoc or <quote>anonymous</quote> code blocks. Functions can now be called using named parameters. <link linkend=\"plpgsql\">PL/pgSQL</link> is now installed by default, and <link linkend=\"plperl\">PL/Perl</link> and <link linkend=\"plpython\">PL/Python</link> have been enhanced in several ways, including support for Python3."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1179(para) 
msgid "Full support for <link linkend=\"install-windows\">64-bit <productname>Windows</productname></link>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1186(para) 
msgid "More advanced reporting queries, including additional windowing options (<literal>PRECEDING</literal> and <literal>FOLLOWING</literal>) and the ability to control the order in which values are fed to aggregate functions."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1194(para) 
msgid "New trigger features, including SQL-standard-compliant <link linkend=\"sql-createtrigger\">per-column triggers</link> and conditional trigger execution."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1203(para) 
msgid "<link linkend=\"sql-createtable-compatibility\">Deferrable unique constraints</link>. Mass updates to unique keys are now possible without trickery."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1211(para) 
msgid "<link linkend=\"ddl-constraints-exclusion\">Exclusion constraints</link>. These provide a generalized version of unique constraints, allowing enforcement of complex conditions."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1219(para) 
msgid "New and enhanced security features, including RADIUS authentication, LDAP authentication improvements, and a new contrib module <link linkend=\"passwordcheck\"><filename>passwordcheck</filename></link> for testing password strength."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1228(para) 
msgid "New high-performance implementation of the <link linkend=\"sql-listen\"><command>LISTEN</command></link>/<link linkend=\"sql-notify\"><command>NOTIFY</command></link> feature. Pending events are now stored in a memory-based queue rather than a table. Also, a <quote>payload</quote> string can be sent with each event, rather than transmitting just an event name as before."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1239(para) 
msgid "New implementation of <link linkend=\"sql-vacuum\"><command>VACUUM FULL</command></link>. This command now rewrites the entire table and indexes, rather than moving individual rows to compact space. It is substantially faster in most cases, and no longer results in index bloat."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1249(para) 
msgid "New contrib module <link linkend=\"pgupgrade\"><filename>pg_upgrade</filename></link> to support in-place upgrades from 8.3 or 8.4 to 9.0."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1257(para) 
msgid "Multiple performance enhancements for specific types of queries, including elimination of unnecessary joins. This helps optimize some automatically-generated queries, such as those produced by object-relational mappers (ORMs)."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1266(para) 
msgid "<link linkend=\"sql-explain \"><command>EXPLAIN</command></link> enhancements. The output is now available in JSON, XML, or YAML format, and includes buffer utilization and other data not previously available."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1274(para) 
msgid "<link linkend=\"hstore\"><filename>hstore</filename></link> improvements, including new functions and greater data capacity."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1282(para) 
msgid "The above items are explained in more detail in the sections below."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1290(title) 
msgid "Migration to Version 9.0"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1292(para) 
msgid "A dump/restore using <application>pg_dump</application>, or use of <application>pg_upgrade</application>, is required for those wishing to migrate data from any previous release."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1299(para) 
msgid "Version 9.0 contains a number of changes that selectively break backwards compatibility in order to support new features and code quality improvements. In particular, users who make extensive use of PL/pgSQL, Point-In-Time Recovery (PITR), or Warm Standby should test their applications because of slight user-visible changes in those areas. Observe the following incompatibilities:"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1309(title) /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:2012(title) 
msgid "Server Settings"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1314(para) 
msgid "Remove server parameter <varname>add_missing_from</varname>, which was defaulted to off for many years (Tom Lane)"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1321(para) 
msgid "Remove server parameter <varname>regex_flavor</varname>, which was defaulted to <link linkend=\"posix-syntax-details\"><literal>advanced</literal></link> for many years (Tom Lane)"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1330(para) 
msgid "<link linkend=\"guc-archive-mode\"><varname>archive_mode</varname></link> now only affects <link linkend=\"guc-archive-command\"><varname>archive_command</varname></link>; a new setting, <link linkend=\"guc-wal-level\"><varname>wal_level</varname></link>, affects the contents of the write-ahead log (Heikki Linnakangas)"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1341(para) 
msgid "<link linkend=\"guc-log-temp-files\"><varname>log_temp_files</varname></link> now uses default file size units of kilobytes (Robert Haas)"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1352(title) /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:2115(title) 
msgid "Queries"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1357(para) 
msgid "When querying a <link linkend=\"ddl-inherit\">parent table</link>, do not do any separate permission checks on child tables scanned as part of the query (Peter Eisentraut)"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1363(para) 
msgid "The SQL standard specifies this behavior, and it is also much more convenient in practice than the former behavior of checking permissions on each child as well as the parent."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1375(title) /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:2675(title) 
msgid "Data Types"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1380(para) 
msgid "<link linkend=\"datatype-binary\"><type>bytea</type></link> output now appears in hex format by default (Peter Eisentraut)"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1385(para) 
msgid "The server parameter <link linkend=\"guc-bytea-output\"><varname>bytea_output</varname></link> can be used to select the traditional output format if needed for compatibility."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1394(para) 
msgid "Array input now considers only plain ASCII whitespace characters to be potentially ignorable; it will never ignore non-ASCII characters, even if they are whitespace according to some locales (Tom Lane)"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1400(para) 
msgid "This avoids some corner cases where array values could be interpreted differently depending on the server's locale settings."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1407(para) 
msgid "Improve standards compliance of <link linkend=\"functions-similarto-regexp\"><literal>SIMILAR TO</literal></link> patterns and SQL-style <function>substring()</function> patterns (Tom Lane)"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1413(para) 
msgid "This includes treating <literal>?</literal> and <literal>{...}</literal> as pattern metacharacters, while they were simple literal characters before; that corresponds to new features added in SQL:2008. Also, <literal>^</literal> and <literal>$</literal> are now treated as simple literal characters; formerly they were treated as metacharacters, as if the pattern were following POSIX rather than SQL rules. Also, in SQL-standard <function>substring()</function>, use of parentheses for nesting no longer interferes with capturing of a substring. Also, processing of bracket expressions (character classes) is now more standards-compliant."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1428(para) 
msgid "Reject negative length values in 3-parameter <link linkend=\"functions-string-sql\"><function>substring()</function></link> for bit strings, per the SQL standard (Tom Lane)"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1436(para) 
msgid "Make <function>date_trunc</function> truncate rather than round when reducing precision of fractional seconds (Tom Lane)"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1441(para) 
msgid "The code always acted this way for integer-based dates/times. Now float-based dates/times behave similarly."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1452(title) 
msgid "Object Renaming"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1457(para) 
msgid "Tighten enforcement of column name consistency during <command>RENAME</command> when a child table inherits the same column from multiple unrelated parents (KaiGai Kohei)"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1465(para) 
msgid "No longer automatically rename indexes and index columns when the underlying table columns are renamed (Tom Lane)"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1470(para) 
msgid "Administrators can still rename such indexes and columns manually. This change will require an update of the JDBC driver, and possibly other drivers, so that unique indexes are correctly recognized after a rename."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1478(para) 
msgid "<command>CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION</command> can no longer change the declared names of function parameters (Pavel Stehule)"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1483(para) 
msgid "In order to avoid creating ambiguity in named-parameter calls, it is no longer allowed to change the aliases for input parameters in the declaration of an existing function (although names can still be assigned to previously unnamed parameters). You now have to <command>DROP</command> and recreate the function to do that."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1497(title) 
msgid "PL/pgSQL"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1502(para) 
msgid "PL/pgSQL now throws an error if a variable name conflicts with a column name used in a query (Tom Lane)"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1507(para) 
msgid "The former behavior was to bind ambiguous names to PL/pgSQL variables in preference to query columns, which often resulted in surprising misbehavior. Throwing an error allows easy detection of ambiguous situations. Although it's recommended that functions encountering this type of error be modified to remove the conflict, the old behavior can be restored if necessary via the configuration parameter <link linkend=\"plpgsql-var-subst\"><varname>plpgsql.variable_conflict</varname></link>, or via the per-function option <literal>#variable_conflict</literal>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1520(para) 
msgid "PL/pgSQL no longer allows variable names that match certain SQL reserved words (Tom Lane)"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1525(para) 
msgid "This is a consequence of aligning the PL/pgSQL parser to match the core SQL parser more closely. If necessary, variable names can be double-quoted to avoid this restriction."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1533(para) 
msgid "PL/pgSQL now requires columns of composite results to match the expected type modifier as well as base type (Pavel Stehule, Tom Lane)"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1538(para) 
msgid "For example, if a column of the result type is declared as <literal>NUMERIC(30,2)</literal>, it is no longer acceptable to return a <literal>NUMERIC</literal> of some other precision in that column. Previous versions neglected to check the type modifier and would thus allow result rows that didn't actually conform to the declared restrictions."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1548(para) 
msgid "PL/pgSQL now treats selection into composite fields more consistently (Tom Lane)"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1553(para) 
msgid "Formerly, a statement like <literal>SELECT ... INTO <replaceable>rec</replaceable>.<replaceable>fld</replaceable> FROM ...</literal> was treated as a scalar assignment even if the record field <replaceable>fld</replaceable> was of composite type. Now it is treated as a record assignment, the same as when the <literal>INTO</literal> target is a regular variable of composite type. So the values to be assigned to the field's subfields should be written as separate columns of the <command>SELECT</command> list, not as a <literal>ROW(...)</literal> construct as in previous versions."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1565(para) 
msgid "If you need to do this in a way that will work in both 9.0 and previous releases, you can write something like <literal><replaceable>rec</replaceable>.<replaceable>fld</replaceable> := ROW(...) FROM ...</literal>."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1573(para) 
msgid "Remove PL/pgSQL's <literal>RENAME</literal> declaration (Tom Lane)"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1577(para) 
msgid "Instead of <literal>RENAME</literal>, use <link linkend=\"plpgsql-declaration-alias\"><literal>ALIAS</literal></link>, which can now create an alias for any variable, not only dollar sign parameter names (such as <literal>$1</literal>) as before."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1589(title) 
msgid "Other Incompatibilities"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1594(para) 
msgid "Deprecate use of <literal>=&gt;</literal> as an operator name (Robert Haas)"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1598(para) 
msgid "Future versions of <productname>PostgreSQL</productname> will probably reject this operator name entirely, in order to support the SQL-standard notation for named function parameters. For the moment, it is still allowed, but a warning is emitted when such an operator is defined."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1608(para) /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:4179(para) 
msgid "Remove support for platforms that don't have a working 64-bit integer data type (Tom Lane)"
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1613(para) 
msgid "It is believed all still-supported platforms have working 64-bit integer data types."
msgstr ""

#: /tmp/cicero-Bcej/release-9.0.xml:1625(para) 
msgid "Version 9.0 has an unprecedented number of new major features, and over 200 enhancements, improvements, new commands, new functions, and other changes."
msgstr ""

